therne, Cheshire, England, United Kingdom":"Rostherne, Cheshire, England, United Kingdom","Rostherne, Cheshire, England":"Rostherne, Cheshire, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"de","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Dilip, Anirban, Gopal, Alok, Anindya, Arunava, Asit, Asok, Dibyendu, Goutam, Indra, Indranil.","Indian: variant of   Dey  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Dey","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Ashit, Indu, Naina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Mainwaring","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English (of Norman origin): habitational name from Mesnil-Varin in Saint-Paër (Seine-Maritime, Haute-Normandie). The placename means ‘domain of Warin’ (see   Waring  ). Compare   Manwaring   and   Mandry  .","Irish: adopted for <b>Ó Manaráin</b>, see   Mannering   2."],"variants":[{"name":"Manwaring","meanings":["English (of Norman origin): variant of   Mainwaring  ."]},{"name":"Waring","meanings":["English (Lancashire and Yorkshire): variant of   Warren  , from the Norman personal name <i>Warin</i>, derived from ancient Germanic <i>Warino</i>, a short form of various compound names based on the element <i>warin</i> ‘protection, shelter’ or ‘guard’. The name was popular in France and among the Normans (see   Guerin  )."]}]},{"name":"Robert","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["One of the many French names of Germanic origin that were introduced into Britain by the Normans; it has since remained in continuous use. It is derived from the nearly synonymous elements <i>hrōd</i> ‘fame’ + <i>berht</i> ‘bright, famous’, and had a native Old English predecessor of similar form (<i>Hreodbeorht</i>), which was supplanted by the Norman name. Two dukes of Normandy in the 11th century bore the name: the father of  William the Conqueror  (sometimes identified with the legendary Robert the Devil), and his eldest son. It was borne also by three kings of Scotland, notably  Robert the Bruce  (  1274–1329 ), who freed Scotland from English domination. The altered short form <i>Bob</i> is very common, but <i>Hob</i> and <i>Dob</i>, which were common in the Middle Ages and gave rise to surnames, are extinct.  See also  Rupert ."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705187,"age":9,"year":"1215","julianDay":2164830,"title":"Magna Carta","description":"King John of England agreed to a charter of rights called the Magna Carta. The document was originally drafted by the Archbishop of Canterbury to establish peace between King John and a group of rebel barons. The Magna Carta was completed in 1215 and is now considered to be one of the greatest constitutional documents of all time.","url":"https://www.nationalarchives.gov.uk/education/medieval/magna-carta/","urlTitle":"National Archives - Magna Carta","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705188,"age":18,"year":"1224","julianDay":2168117,"title":"France Declares War on England","description":"France declared war on England as Louis VIII of France attacked Poitou and northern Gascony.","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705189,"age":53,"year":"1259","julianDay":2180901,"title":"100 Years of Conflict Between England and France Ends","description":"Treaty of Paris was signed on December 4, 1259, which ended 100 years of conflict between England and France.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Treaty_of_Paris_(1259)","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Treaty of Paris 1259","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705190,"age":84,"year":"1290","julianDay":2192224,"title":"Jews Expelled From England","description":"After years of anti-Semitic behavior, King Edward I expelled Jews from England in 1290.","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705191,"age":109,"year":"1315","toYear":"1317","julianDay":2201354,"title":"Famine Strikes Europe","description":"A famine caused by cold winters and wet summers across Europe caused millions to die due to starvation. Desperation from hunger caused high levels of crime, stampedes in bread lines in London, infanticide, and even cannibalism throughout Europe.","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"Mrs. Robert de Mainwaring was born in 1206, in Rostherne, Cheshire, England. She had at least 1 son and 1 daughter with Robert de Mainwaring. She died in Rostherne, Cheshire, England, United Kingdom."},"et":{"1206–":"1206–Surnud","1208–1235":"1208–1235","1224–Male":"1224–Surnud","1235–1300":"1235–1300","1206–Female":"1206–Surnud","1206":"1206","1315":"1315","1259":"1259","1215":"1215","1235":"1235","1224":"1224","1300":"1300","about 1224":"umbes 1224","1208":"1208","1317":"1317","1290":"1290","Rostherne, Cheshire, England, United Kingdom":"Rostherne, Cheshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Rostherne, Cheshire, England":"Rostherne, Cheshire, England"},"fi":{"1206–":"1206–Kuollut","1208–1235":"1208–1235","1224–Male":"1224–Kuollut","1235–1300":"1235–1300","1206–Female":"1206–Kuollut","1206":"1206","1315":"1315","1259":"1259","1215":"1215","1235":"1235","1224":"1224","1300":"1300","about 1224":"noin 1224","1208":"1208","1317":"1317","1290":"1290","Rostherne, Cheshire, England, United Kingdom":"Rostherne, Cheshire, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","Rostherne, Cheshire, England":"Rostherne, Cheshire, England"},"fr":{"1206–":"1206–Décédée","1208–1235":"1208–1235","1224–Male":"1224–Décédé","1235–1300":"1235–1300","1206–Female":"1206–Décédée","1206":"1206","1315":"1315","1259":"1259","1215":"1215","1235":"1235","1224":"1224","1300":"1300","about 1224":"environ 1224","1208":"1208","1317":"1317","1290":"1290","Rostherne, Cheshire, Engl